# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1905-philadelphia-athletics-season
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1905-philadelphia-athletics-season/100-000-infield] The **$100,000 infield** was the infield of the Philadelphia Athletics in the early 1910s.
[src:1905-philadelphia-athletics-season/100-000-infield] The $100,000 infield consisted of first baseman Stuffy McInnis, second baseman Eddie Collins, shortstop Jack Barry and third baseman Frank "Home Run" Baker.
[src:1905-philadelphia-athletics-season/100-000-infield] According to the *Encyclopædia Britannica*, the nickname reflects "the purported combined market value of the foursome", which is equivalent to about $2.44 million in 2024.
[src:1905-philadelphia-athletics-season/100-000-infield] Baseball historian Bill James rated the 1914 edition of the $100,000 infield the greatest infield of all time, and also ranked the 1912 and 1913 editions in the top five all time.
[src:1905-philadelphia-athletics-season/100-000-infield] The $100,000 infield helped the Athletics win four American League championships in five years—1910, 1911, 1913 and 1914—and win the World Series in 1910, 1911 and 1913.
[src:1905-philadelphia-athletics-season/100-000-infield] The group was broken up after losing the 1914 World Series as a result of the financial pressures resulting from the emergence of the Federal League.
[src:1905-philadelphia-athletics-season/100-000-infield] Two members—Collins and Baker—have been inducted into the Baseball Hall of Fame.
[src:1905-philadelphia-athletics-season/100-000-infield] Collins was the first member of the $100,000 infield to join the Athletics.
[src:1905-philadelphia-athletics-season/100-000-infield] He debuted on September 17, 1906, after playing college ball at Columbia University.
[src:1905-philadelphia-athletics-season/100-000-infield] In 1906 and 1907, he played 20 games for the Athletics, mostly at shortstop.
[src:1905-philadelphia-athletics-season/100-000-infield] In 1908, he took over as the Athletics' regular second baseman, replacing Danny Murphy, who moved to the outfield.
[src:1905-philadelphia-athletics-season/100-000-infield] During the $100,000 infield years from 1910 to 1914, he played 738 games, getting 922 hits in 2,677 at bats for a batting average of .344.
[src:1905-philadelphia-athletics-season/100-000-infield] He led the American League in runs in 1912, 1913 and 1914, stolen bases in 1910, singles in 1913 and times on base in 1914.
[src:1905-philadelphia-athletics-season/100-000-infield] He also finished in the top ten in the American League in batting average, on-base percentage, hits, stolen bases, singles and times on base every year from 1910 through 1914.
[src:1905-philadelphia-athletics-season/100-000-infield] In addition, he finished in the top ten in American Most Valuable Player voting every year from 1911 through 1914, winning the Most Valuable Player award in 1914.
[src:1905-philadelphia-athletics-season/100-000-infield] He was sold to the Chicago White Sox after the 1914 season as Athletics' manager Connie Mack attempted to respond to the financial pressures brought on by the newly formed Federal League, breaking up the $100,000 infield.
[src:1905-philadelphia-athletics-season/100-000-infield] He returned to Mack and the Athletics in 1927, finishing his career playing 12 games for the Athletics in their 1929 and 1930 World Championship seasons.
[src:1905-philadelphia-athletics-season/100-000-infield] He was elected to the Hall of Fame in 1939.
[src:1905-philadelphia-athletics-season/100-000-infield] Barry was the next to join the Athletics, debuting on July 13, 1908, after playing for the College of the Holy Cross.
[src:1905-philadelphia-athletics-season/100-000-infield] Between 1910 and 1914, Barry played 686 games for the Athletics, getting 607 hits in 2,334 at bats for a batting average of .260.
[src:1905-philadelphia-athletics-season/100-000-infield] He finished in the American League top ten in sacrifice hits every year from 1911 through 1914, and ranked fifth in the American League in runs batted in in 1913.
[src:1905-philadelphia-athletics-season/100-000-infield] But his primary contributions were on defense, where he had a strong arm, enormous range and sure hands, and was able to work out innovative plays with his good friend Collins, such as a defense against the double steal.
[src:1905-philadelphia-athletics-season/100-000-infield] He finished in the top 20 in Most Valuable Player voting every year from 1911 through 1914, with his best showing a ninth-place finish in 1913.
[src:1905-philadelphia-athletics-season/100-000-infield] He was sold to the Boston Red Sox in the middle of the 1915 season, where he moved to second base and played on the Red Sox' 1915 and 1916 World Championship teams.
[src:1905-philadelphia-athletics-season/100-000-infield] He missed the Red Sox 1918 Championship season due to service in the U.S.
[src:1905-philadelphia-athletics-season/100-000-infield] Baker also joined the Athletics in 1908, debuting on September 21.
[src:1905-philadelphia-athletics-season/100-000-infield] He became the Athletics regular third baseman in 1909, and led the American League in triples that season.
[src:1905-philadelphia-athletics-season/100-000-infield] Between 1910 and 1914, Baker played 742 games for the Athletics, getting 929 hits in 2,864 at bats for a batting average of .324.
[src:1905-philadelphia-athletics-season/100-000-infield] He led the American League in home runs every year from 1911 through 1914, and led the league in runs batted in during 1912 and 1913.
[src:1905-philadelphia-athletics-season/100-000-infield] He also finished in the top ten in batting average, slugging percentage, on-base percentage and times on base every year from 1911 through 1914, and finished in the top ten in runs scored, hits, doubles, total bases, extra base hits and runs batted in every year from 1910 through 1914.
[src:1905-philadelphia-athletics-season/100-000-infield] He finished in the top ten in the American League Most Valuable Player voting every year from 1911 through 1914, finishing third in 1914, his highest showing.
[src:1905-philadelphia-athletics-season/100-000-infield] Baker was the hero of the 1911 World Series, hitting two home runs to help the Athletics win the series, which earned him the nickname "Home Run" Baker.
[src:1905-philadelphia-athletics-season/100-000-infield] Baker held out the 1915 season when manager and owner Connie Mack refused to increase his salary, and was sold to the New York Yankees in 1916 after American League president Ban Johnson intervened.
[src:1905-philadelphia-athletics-season/100-000-infield] He finished his career as the third baseman for the Yankees pennant-winning teams in 1921 and 1922.
[src:1905-philadelphia-athletics-season/100-000-infield] Baker was elected to the Hall of Fame in 1955.
[src:1905-philadelphia-athletics-season/100-000-infield] McInnis was the final member of the $100,000 infield to join.
[src:1905-philadelphia-athletics-season/100-000-infield] He started his career as an 18-year-old little-used backup infielder for the Athletics in 1909, and played a little more in 1910.
[src:1905-philadelphia-athletics-season/100-000-infield] In 1909 and 1910, he played more games backing up Barry at shortstop than at any other position.
[src:1905-philadelphia-athletics-season/100-000-infield] Before the 1911 season, Mack decided to make McInnis his regular first baseman, replacing the popular veteran Harry Davis, although McInnis did have to begin the season as the Athletics' shortstop when Barry became ill before taking over at first base.
[src:1905-philadelphia-athletics-season/100-000-infield] Defensively as a first baseman, he was known for having exceptional reach.
[src:1905-philadelphia-athletics-season/100-000-infield] Between 1910 and 1914, McInnis played 614 games for the Athletics, getting 715 hits in 2,228 at bats for a batting average of .321.
[src:1905-philadelphia-athletics-season/100-000-infield] He led the American League in singles in 1914, and finished in the top ten in batting average, hits, total bases, runs batted in and singles every year from 1912 through 1914.
[src:1905-philadelphia-athletics-season/100-000-infield] In both 1912 and 1913, he also finished in the top ten in slugging percentage and on-base percentage.
[src:1905-philadelphia-athletics-season/100-000-infield] He received Most Valuable Player votes every season from 1911 through 1914, finishing seventh in both 1913 and 1914.
[src:1905-philadelphia-athletics-season/100-000-infield] McInnis is the only member of the $100,000 infield to remain with the Athletics beyond 1915.
[src:1905-philadelphia-athletics-season/100-000-infield] He was eventually traded to the Boston Red Sox in 1918 in exchange for Larry Gardner, Hick Cady and Tilly Walker, where he played on Boston's 1918 World Championship team.
[src:1905-philadelphia-athletics-season/100-000-infield] He also reteamed with Barry on the 1919 Boston Red Sox.
[src:1905-philadelphia-athletics-season/100-000-infield] Before finishing his career in 1927 he also played with the Cleveland Indians, Boston Braves, Pittsburgh Pirates and Philadelphia Phillies.
[src:1905-philadelphia-athletics-season/1901-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1901 Chicago White Stockings season** was their first season as a major league team, and their second season in Chicago.
[src:1905-philadelphia-athletics-season/1901-chicago-white-stockings-season] It was also the inaugural season of American League as a major league.
[src:1905-philadelphia-athletics-season/1901-chicago-white-stockings-season] The White Stockings had a very balanced lineup, which was led by outfielders Dummy Hoy and Fielder Jones, and scored the most runs in the AL.
[src:1905-philadelphia-athletics-season/1901-chicago-white-stockings-season] They relied primarily on speed, as Frank Isbell, Sam Mertes, and Jones finished 1–2–3 in stolen bases.
[src:1905-philadelphia-athletics-season/1901-chicago-white-stockings-season] The pitching staff was anchored by Clark Griffith, who went 24–7 with a 2.67 ERA.
[src:1905-philadelphia-athletics-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] The **1901 major league baseball season** was contested from April 18 through October 6, 1901.
[src:1905-philadelphia-athletics-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] It was the inaugural major league season for the American League (AL) (having previously been the minor league Western League), with the Chicago White Stockings winning the AL pennant.
[src:1905-philadelphia-athletics-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] In the National League (NL), in operation since 1876, the Pittsburgh Pirates won the NL pennant.
[src:1905-philadelphia-athletics-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] This was the first season of the modern era.
[src:1905-philadelphia-athletics-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] This would be the only season in which the Milwaukee Brewers played, as the team would relocate to St.
[src:1905-philadelphia-athletics-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] Louis, Missouri for the following season as the St.
[src:1905-philadelphia-athletics-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] Louis Browns (before that team relocated to Baltimore, Maryland as the modern Baltimore Orioles in 1954, where they remain to this day.
[src:1905-philadelphia-athletics-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] The Baltimore Orioles of this season would fold following the 1902 season).
[src:1905-philadelphia-athletics-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] The 1901 schedule consisted of 140 games for all teams in the American League and National League, each of which had eight teams.
[src:1905-philadelphia-athletics-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] Each team was scheduled to play 20 games against the other seven teams of their respective league.
[src:1905-philadelphia-athletics-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] This format had previously been used by the National League during their 1888–1891 seasons.
[src:1905-philadelphia-athletics-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] This format would last until 1904, which saw an increase of games played.
[src:1905-philadelphia-athletics-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] National League Opening Day took place on April 18 with a game between the Brooklyn Superbas and the Philadelphia Phillies, while American League Opening Day did not take place until April 24, with a game between the Chicago White Stockings and the Cleveland Bluebirds.
[src:1905-philadelphia-athletics-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] The American League would see its final day of the season on September 28, while the National League would see its final day of the season on October 6.
[src:1905-philadelphia-athletics-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] On February 27, 1901, the National League Rules Committee announced several rule changes, effective immediately.
[src:1905-philadelphia-athletics-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] Blue laws restricted Sunday activities in several localities, causing several teams to play at ballparks in a different locality.
[src:1905-philadelphia-athletics-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] 15 tie games (8 in AL, 7 in NL), which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again), occurred throughout the season.
[src:1905-philadelphia-athletics-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] Any team shown in small text indicates a previous team a player was on during the season.
[src:1905-philadelphia-athletics-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] The Cincinnati Reds would play their final game at League Park, on October 6 during a doubleheader against the St.
[src:1905-philadelphia-athletics-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] Louis Cardinals, moving into the Palace of the Fans for the start of the 1902 season.
[src:1905-philadelphia-athletics-season/1901-philadelphia-athletics-season] The **1901 Philadelphia Athletics season** involved the A's finishing fourth in the American League with a record of 74 wins and 62 losses.
[src:1905-philadelphia-athletics-season/1901-philadelphia-athletics-season] The franchise that would become the modern Athletics originated in 1901 as a new franchise in the American League.
[src:1905-philadelphia-athletics-season/1901-philadelphia-athletics-season] The Western League had been renamed the American League in 1900 by league president Bancroft (Ban) Johnson, and declared itself the second major league in 1901.
[src:1905-philadelphia-athletics-season/1901-philadelphia-athletics-season] In 1901, Johnson created new franchises in the east and eliminated some franchises in the west.
[src:1905-philadelphia-athletics-season/1901-philadelphia-athletics-season] Philadelphia seems to have been a new franchise created to compete with the National League's Philadelphia Phillies.
[src:1905-philadelphia-athletics-season/1901-philadelphia-athletics-season] Former catcher Connie Mack was recruited to manage the club.
[src:1905-philadelphia-athletics-season/1901-philadelphia-athletics-season] Mack in turn persuaded Phillies minority owner Ben Shibe as well as others to invest in the team, which would be called the **Philadelphia Athletics**.
[src:1905-philadelphia-athletics-season/1901-philadelphia-athletics-season] He himself bought a 25 percent interest.
[src:1905-philadelphia-athletics-season/1901-philadelphia-athletics-season] In 1901, Nap Lajoie jumped from the Phillies to the crosstown Philadelphia Athletics, owned by Connie Mack.
[src:1905-philadelphia-athletics-season/1901-philadelphia-athletics-season] Lajoie's batting average that year was .426, still a league record.
[src:1905-philadelphia-athletics-season/1901-philadelphia-athletics-season] The same year Lajoie became the second major leaguer to be intentionally walked with the bases loaded after Abner Dalrymple in 1881.
[src:1905-philadelphia-athletics-season/1902-philadelphia-athletics-season] The **1902 Philadelphia Athletics season** was a season in American baseball.
[src:1905-philadelphia-athletics-season/1902-philadelphia-athletics-season] The team finished first in the American League with a record of 83 wins and 53 losses.
[src:1905-philadelphia-athletics-season/1902-philadelphia-athletics-season] In 1902, the Philadelphia Phillies obtained an injunction, effective only in Pennsylvania, barring Athletics' second baseman Nap Lajoie from playing baseball for any team other than the Phillies.
[src:1905-philadelphia-athletics-season/1902-philadelphia-athletics-season] Lajoie had played for the Athletics in 1901, and appeared in just one game in 1902 before the injunction went into effect.
[src:1905-philadelphia-athletics-season/1902-philadelphia-athletics-season] The American League responded by transferring Lajoie's contract to the Cleveland Bronchos, who were subsequently known as the "Naps" in Lajoie's honor for several seasons.
[src:1905-philadelphia-athletics-season/1902-philadelphia-athletics-season] Following the A's pennant winning season, the *Philadelphia Inquirer* organized a championship parade for the team through the city on Monday night, September 30, 1902.
[src:1905-philadelphia-athletics-season/1902-philadelphia-athletics-season] The team proceeded in open carriages and were reviewed by Philadelphia Mayor Ashbridge in front of the *Inquirer'*s building on Market Street.
[src:1905-philadelphia-athletics-season/1902-philadelphia-athletics-season] "There were more than 25,000 base ball enthusiasts from Philadelphia and nearly every town within a radius of twenty miles of the city in the parade.
[src:1905-philadelphia-athletics-season/1902-philadelphia-athletics-season] A thousand effigies of the "white elephant" were carried by the paraders.
[src:1905-philadelphia-athletics-season/1902-philadelphia-athletics-season] There were fifteen bands and twenty fife and drum corps in line to furnish music for the marchers." It was estimated that more than 200,000 turned out for the parade.
[src:1905-philadelphia-athletics-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The **1903 Boston Americans season** was the third season for the professional baseball franchise that later became known as the Boston Red Sox.
[src:1905-philadelphia-athletics-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The Americans finished first in the American League (AL) with a record of 91 wins and 47 losses, 14+1⁄2 games ahead of the Philadelphia Athletics.
[src:1905-philadelphia-athletics-season/1903-boston-americans-season] Boston went on to participate in the first World Series held between the AL and National League (NL) champions.
[src:1905-philadelphia-athletics-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The Americans won the 1903 World Series in eight games over the Pittsburgh Pirates.
[src:1905-philadelphia-athletics-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The team was managed by Jimmy Collins and played its home games at Huntington Avenue Grounds.
[src:1905-philadelphia-athletics-season/1903-boston-americans-season] Prior to the regular season, the team held spring training in Macon, Georgia.
[src:1905-philadelphia-athletics-season/1903-boston-americans-season] Cy Young was a coach for the Mercer University baseball team, also based in Macon.
[src:1905-philadelphia-athletics-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The Boston Americans played an exhibition game against Mercer University (with Cy Young pitching for Mercer) on March 23; the outcome being a 13─2 victory for Boston.
[src:1905-philadelphia-athletics-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The team's longest losing streak was three games, which occurred twice; April 20–23 and September 22–23.
[src:1905-philadelphia-athletics-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The team's longest game was 12 innings, which occurred three times.
[src:1905-philadelphia-athletics-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The offense was led by Buck Freeman, who hit 13 home runs and had 104 RBIs, and Patsy Dougherty with a .331 batting average.
[src:1905-philadelphia-athletics-season/1903-boston-americans-season] It was Freeman's third consecutive season with at least 100 RBIs.
[src:1905-philadelphia-athletics-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The pitching staff was led by Cy Young, who made 40 appearances (35 starts) and pitched 34 complete games with a 28–9 record and 2.08 ERA, while striking out 176 in 341+2⁄3 innings.
[src:1905-philadelphia-athletics-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The team had two other 20-game winners; Bill Dinneen (21–13) and Tom Hughes (20–7).
[src:1905-philadelphia-athletics-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The team had three games end in a tie; July 31 at Washington, August 29 at Washington, and September 25 vs.
[src:1905-philadelphia-athletics-season/1903-boston-americans-season] Tie games are not counted in league standings, but player statistics during tie games are counted.
[src:1905-philadelphia-athletics-season/1903-boston-americans-season] Boston had an 11-game winning streak from May 28 through June 8, to put themselves in the AL lead.
[src:1905-philadelphia-athletics-season/1903-boston-americans-season] While they briefly fell into second place in mid-June, behind Philadelphia, Boston then won 9-of-10 to recapture the lead, which they held through the end of the season.
[src:1905-philadelphia-athletics-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The Americans met the Pittsburgh Pirates in the first modern World Series, an agreement between the AL and the NL as a post-season tournament.
[src:1905-philadelphia-athletics-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The "Amerks" won the best-of-nine series in eight games; after falling behind, 3–1, they won four games in a row, clinching the championship at their home field, the Huntington Avenue Grounds, in Boston.
[src:1905-philadelphia-athletics-season/1903-philadelphia-athletics-season] The **1903 Philadelphia Athletics season** was a season in American baseball.
[src:1905-philadelphia-athletics-season/1903-philadelphia-athletics-season] The team finished second in the American League with a record of 75 wins and 60 losses, 14½ games behind the Boston Americans.
[src:1905-philadelphia-athletics-season/1903-philadelphia-athletics-season] The A's had begun play in 1901 but National League and American League teams did not play each other in 1901 or 1902 as the leagues battled to expand their markets and customers.
[src:1905-philadelphia-athletics-season/1903-philadelphia-athletics-season] After the leagues made peace after 1902, the Phillies and Athletics scheduled a preseason series for the local championship.
[src:1905-philadelphia-athletics-season/1903-philadelphia-athletics-season] The Player League’s Philadelphia Athletics and American Association Athletics had contested the local championship with the Phillies between 1883 and 1890.
[src:1905-philadelphia-athletics-season/1903-philadelphia-athletics-season] Prior to the start of the series, the Athletics players threatened not to play unless they were paid a percentage of the gate receipts.
[src:1905-philadelphia-athletics-season/1903-philadelphia-athletics-season] The Phillies and Athletics played five of nine scheduled games; the Phillies defeated the Athletics, 4 games to 1.
[src:1905-philadelphia-athletics-season/1903-philadelphia-athletics-season] The series was scheduled to begin on April 4, 1903 at the Phillies’ Philadelphia Ball Park but was called off due to rain.
[src:1905-philadelphia-athletics-season/1903-philadelphia-athletics-season] Games scheduled for April 7, 1903 at the Phillies’ park and April 8, 1903 at the Athletics’ Columbia Park were also canceled due to rain and wet grounds, along with the final scheduled game of the series on April 14, 1903 at the Phillies’ park.
[src:1905-philadelphia-athletics-season/1903-philadelphia-athletics-season] The Philadelphia Phillies and Athletics played a postseason series for the local championship in addition to the preseason series played in April.
[src:1905-philadelphia-athletics-season/1903-philadelphia-athletics-season] The teams played seven of ten games scheduled; games scheduled for October 8, 1903; October 9, 1903; and October 10, 1903 were canceled due to rain.
[src:1905-philadelphia-athletics-season/1903-philadelphia-athletics-season] The Athletics won the series, 4 games to 3.
[src:1905-philadelphia-athletics-season/1903-philadelphia-athletics-season] All of the series games were played at the Athletics’ Columbia Park with each team alternating as the home team.
[src:1905-philadelphia-athletics-season/1903-philadelphia-athletics-season] The Phillies’ Philadelphia Ball Park’s had collapsed on August 8 1903 leaving four dead, and closing the ballpark for the balance of the season.
[src:1905-philadelphia-athletics-season/1903-philadelphia-athletics-season] After the 1903 season, the Phillies had won 7 and the Athletics had won 5 of the 12 total games played in the city series.
[src:1905-philadelphia-athletics-season/1905-philadelphia-athletics-season] The **1905 Philadelphia Athletics season** was a season in American baseball.
[src:1905-philadelphia-athletics-season/1905-philadelphia-athletics-season] The team finished first in the American League with a record of 92 wins and 56 losses, winning their second pennant.
[src:1905-philadelphia-athletics-season/1905-philadelphia-athletics-season] They went on to face the New York Giants in the 1905 World Series, losing 4 games to 1.
[src:1905-philadelphia-athletics-season/1905-philadelphia-athletics-season] The pitching staff featured three future Hall of Famers: Rube Waddell, Eddie Plank, and Chief Bender.
[src:1905-philadelphia-athletics-season/1905-philadelphia-athletics-season] Waddell easily won the pitching triple crown in 1905, with 27 wins, 287 strikeouts, and a 1.48 earned run average.
[src:1905-philadelphia-athletics-season/1905-philadelphia-athletics-season] The Athletics played eight games against the Philadelphia Phillies for the local championship in the pre-season city series.
[src:1905-philadelphia-athletics-season/1905-philadelphia-athletics-season] The Athletics and Phillies tied in the series, 4 games to 4.
[src:1905-philadelphia-athletics-season/1905-philadelphia-athletics-season] Two games scheduled for April 5, 1905 at the Phillies' Philadelphia Ball Park, and for April 6, 1905 at the Athletics' Columbia Park were called off on account of wet grounds.
[src:1905-philadelphia-athletics-season/1905-philadelphia-athletics-season] The A's all-time record against the Phillies was 14–14 through 1905.
[src:1905-philadelphia-athletics-season/1905-philadelphia-athletics-season] The A's offense scored the most runs in the league.
[src:1905-philadelphia-athletics-season/1905-philadelphia-athletics-season] Slugger Harry Davis led all players in home runs, runs scored, and runs batted in.
[src:1905-philadelphia-athletics-season/1905-philadelphia-athletics-season] McGraw and Mack had known each other for years, and McGraw accepted it graciously.
